TY  - JOUR
T1  - Ascientific Beliefs About Large Organizations and Adaptation to Change
AU  - Steiner, John F.
AU  - Edmunds, Stahrl W.
Y1  - 1979/01/01
PY  - 1979
DA  - 1979/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1979.4289195
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1979.4289195
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 107
EP  - 112
VL  - 4
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The public interest and the preservation of democracy depend upon trustworthy leaders and a reasonable citizenry. The reasonableness of public belief is examined in the context of present prelogical and conspiracy beliefs in American society. The common belief that a small and unethical power elite dominates business and politics gives rise to conspiracy theories of governance; and these conspiracies, as in ages past, must be exorcised by ceremonies not unlike the Middle Ages. Conceptually, the public has little ability to understand the processes of large organizations; and thus people tend to attribute to them the motives of small group behavior with which they are familiar. The result is a state of incongruity between received belief and real-life observations, which leads to individual stress and several forms of maladaptation which are described in this essay.
AB  - The public interest and the preservation of democracy depend upon trustworthy leaders and a reasonable citizenry. The reasonableness of public belief is examined in the context of present prelogical and conspiracy beliefs in American society. The common belief that a small and unethical power elite dominates business and politics gives rise to conspiracy theories of governance; and these conspiracies, as in ages past, must be exorcised by ceremonies not unlike the Middle Ages. Conceptually, the public has little ability to understand the processes of large organizations; and thus people tend to attribute to them the motives of small group behavior with which they are familiar. The result is a state of incongruity between received belief and real-life observations, which leads to individual stress and several forms of maladaptation which are described in this essay.
